  <h2>Why Dental Health Matters for Your Pet</h2>
  <p>
    Dental disease is one of the most common health problems we see in dogs and cats. Studies show that <strong>over 80% of pets develop some form of dental disease by age three</strong>. Left untreated, dental problems cause more than just bad breath — bacteria from infected gums can enter the bloodstream and affect your pet's heart, liver, and kidneys.
  </p>
  <p>
    At Healthy Paws Animal Hospital, we take a proactive approach to pet dental care. Our goal is to identify and treat oral health issues early, before they cause pain or lead to more serious health complications.
  </p>

  <h2>Our Dental Care Services</h2>

  <h3>Comprehensive Oral Examinations</h3>
  <p>
    Every <a href="/wellness-exams-lake-in-the-hills-il/">wellness exam</a> includes an oral health assessment. Our team examines your pet's teeth, gums, and oral tissues to check for signs of periodontal disease, fractured teeth, oral masses, and other concerns. When we identify issues, we'll walk you through exactly what we've found and recommend next steps.
  </p>

  <h3>Digital Dental Radiography</h3>
  <p>
    What you see above the gumline is only part of the picture. Approximately <strong>60% of each tooth sits below the gumline</strong>, where problems like root abscesses, bone loss, and resorptive lesions can develop silently. Our digital dental X-rays provide detailed images of the entire tooth structure, helping us catch problems that a visual exam alone would miss.
  </p>

  <h3>Professional Teeth Cleaning</h3>
  <p>
    A professional dental cleaning at Healthy Paws involves several steps, all performed while your pet is under safe, monitored anesthesia:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>Full mouth digital dental X-rays</li>
    <li>Scaling to remove plaque and tartar above and below the gumline</li>
    <li>Polishing to smooth tooth surfaces and slow future plaque buildup</li>
    <li>A thorough exam of each tooth and the surrounding gum tissue</li>
    <li>Fluoride treatment to strengthen enamel</li>
    <li>A detailed report of findings and any recommended follow-up care</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Oral Surgery and Extractions</h3>
  <p>
    When a tooth is severely damaged, infected, or causing your pet pain, extraction may be the best option for their comfort and long-term health. Our team performs oral <a href="/surgery/">surgical procedures</a> with careful attention to <a href="/pain-management/">pain management</a>, and we'll discuss all options with you before proceeding.
  </p>

  <h2>Keeping Your Pet's Mouth Healthy at Home</h2>
  <p>
    Professional cleanings are essential, but daily home care makes a real difference between visits. We recommend:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Daily brushing</strong> with pet-safe toothpaste (never use human toothpaste)</li>
    <li><strong>Dental chews and treats</strong> approved by the Veterinary Oral Health Council (VOHC)</li>
    <li><strong>Dental diets</strong> specifically formulated to reduce plaque and tartar</li>
    <li><strong>Water additives</strong> that help control bacteria in your pet's mouth</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    During your pet's appointment, our team is happy to demonstrate brushing technique and help you choose the right products for your pet's needs.
  </p>

  <h2>Dental Care for Senior Pets</h2>
  <p>
    Older pets are especially prone to dental disease, and dental issues can significantly affect their quality of life. If your <a href="/senior-pet-care-lake-in-the-hills-il/">senior pet</a> is eating less, dropping food, or seems less enthusiastic about meals, dental pain may be the cause. We recommend more frequent dental evaluations for pets over seven years of age to stay ahead of age-related oral health changes.
  </p>
